# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bootloader-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Due to their low costs, low power consumption, and low heat generation, ARM processors are useful for light, portable, battery-powered devices, including smartphones, laptops, and tablet computers, as well as embedded systems.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] However, ARM processors are also used for desktops and servers, including Fugaku, the world's fastest supercomputer from 2020 to 2022.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] With over 230 billion ARM chips produced, since at least 2003, and with its dominance increasing every year, ARM is the most widely used family of instruction set architectures.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] There have been several generations of the ARM design.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The original ARM1 used a 32-bit internal structure but had a 26-bit address space that limited it to 64 MB of main memory.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This limitation was removed in the ARMv3 series, which has a 32-bit address space, and several additional generations up to ARMv7 remained 32-bit.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Released in 2011, the ARMv8-A architecture added support for a 64-bit address space and 64-bit arithmetic with its new 32-bit fixed-length instruction set.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Arm Holdings has also released a series of additional instruction sets for different roles: the "Thumb" extensions add both 32- and 16-bit instructions for improved code density, while Jazelle added instructions for directly handling Java bytecode.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] More recent changes include the addition of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) for improved performance or fault tolerance.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Acorn Computers' first widely successful design was the BBC Micro, introduced in December 1981.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This was a relatively conventional machine based on the MOS Technology 6502 CPU but ran at roughly double the performance of competing designs like the Apple II due to its use of faster dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Typical DRAM of the era ran at about 2 MHz; Acorn arranged a deal with Hitachi for a supply of faster 4 MHz parts.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Machines of the era generally shared memory between the processor and the framebuffer, which allowed the processor to quickly update the contents of the screen without having to perform separate input/output (I/O).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] As the timing of the video display is exacting, the video hardware had to have priority access to that memory.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Due to a quirk of the 6502's design, the CPU left the memory untouched for half of the time.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Thus by running the CPU at 1 MHz, the video system could read data during those down times, taking up the total 2 MHz bandwidth of the RAM.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In the BBC Micro, the use of 4 MHz RAM allowed the same technique to be used, but running at twice the speed.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This allowed it to outperform any similar machine on the market.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] 1981 was also the year that the IBM Personal Computer was introduced.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Using the recently introduced Intel 8088, a 16-bit CPU compared to the 6502's 8-bit design, it offered higher overall performance.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Its introduction changed the desktop computer market radically: what had been largely a hobby and gaming market emerging over the prior five years began to change to a must-have business tool where the earlier 8-bit designs simply could not compete.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Even newer 32-bit designs were also coming to market, such as the Motorola 68000 and National Semiconductor NS32016.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Acorn began considering how to compete in this market and produced a new paper design named the Acorn Business Computer.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] They set themselves the goal of producing a machine with ten times the performance of the BBC Micro, but at the same price.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This would outperform and underprice the PC.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] At the same time, the recent introduction of the Apple Lisa brought the graphical user interface (GUI) concept to a wider audience and suggested the future belonged to machines with a GUI.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The Lisa, however, cost $9,995, as it was packed with support chips, large amounts of memory, and a hard disk drive, all very expensive then.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The engineers then began studying all of the CPU designs available.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Their conclusion about the existing 16-bit designs was that they were a lot more expensive and were still "a bit crap", offering only slightly higher performance than their BBC Micro design.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] They also almost always demanded a large number of support chips to operate even at that level, which drove up the cost of the computer as a whole.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] These systems would simply not hit the design goal.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] They also considered the new 32-bit designs, but these cost even more and had the same issues with support chips.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] According to Sophie Wilson, all the processors tested at that time performed about the same, with about a 4 Mbit/s bandwidth.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Two key events led Acorn down the path to ARM.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] One was the publication of a series of reports from the University of California, Berkeley, which suggested that a simple chip design could nevertheless have extremely high performance, much higher than the latest 32-bit designs on the market.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The second was a visit by Steve Furber and Sophie Wilson to the Western Design Center, a company run by Bill Mensch and his sister Kathryn, which had become the logical successor to the MOS team and was offering new versions like the WDC 65C02.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The Acorn team saw high school students producing chip layouts on Apple II machines, which suggested that anyone could do it.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In contrast, a visit to another design firm working on modern 32-bit CPU revealed a team with over a dozen members who were already on revision H of their design and yet it still contained bugs.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This cemented their late 1983 decision to begin their own CPU design, the Acorn RISC Machine.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The original Berkeley RISC designs were in some sense teaching systems, not designed specifically for outright performance.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] To the RISC's basic register-heavy and load/store concepts, ARM added a number of the well-received design notes of the 6502.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Primary among them was the ability to quickly service interrupts, which allowed the machines to offer reasonable input/output performance with no added external hardware.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] To offer interrupts with similar performance as the 6502, the ARM design limited its physical address space to 64 MB of total addressable space, requiring 26 bits of address.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] As instructions were 4 bytes (32 bits) long, and required to be aligned on 4-byte boundaries, the lower 2 bits of an instruction address were always zero.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This meant the program counter (PC) only needed to be 24 bits, allowing it to be stored along with the eight bit processor flags in a single 32-bit register.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] That meant that upon receiving an interrupt, the entire machine state could be saved in a single operation, whereas had the PC been a full 32-bit value, it would require separate operations to store the PC and the status flags.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This decision halved the interrupt overhead.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Another change, and among the most important in terms of practical real-world performance, was the modification of the instruction set to take advantage of page mode DRAM.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Recently introduced, page mode allowed subsequent accesses of memory to run twice as fast if they were roughly in the same location, or "page", in the DRAM chip.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Berkeley's design did not consider page mode and treated all memory equally.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The ARM design added special vector-like memory access instructions, the "S-cycles", that could be used to fill or save multiple registers in a single page using page mode.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This doubled memory performance when they could be used, and was especially important for graphics performance.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The Berkeley RISC designs used register windows to reduce the number of register saves and restores performed in procedure calls; the ARM design did not adopt this.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Wilson developed the instruction set, writing a simulation of the processor in BBC BASIC that ran on a BBC Micro with a second 6502 processor.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This convinced Acorn engineers they were on the right track.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Wilson approached Acorn's CEO, Hermann Hauser, and requested more resources.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Hauser gave his approval and assembled a small team to design the actual processor based on Wilson's instruction set architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The official Acorn RISC Machine project started in October 1983.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Acorn chose VLSI Technology as the "silicon partner", as they were a source of ROMs and custom chips for Acorn.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Acorn provided the design and VLSI provided the layout and production.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The first samples of ARM silicon worked properly when first received and tested on 26 April 1985.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Known as ARM1, these versions ran at 6 MHz.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The first ARM application was as a second processor for the BBC Micro, where it helped in developing simulation software to finish development of the support chips (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), and sped up the CAD software used in ARM2 development.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Wilson subsequently rewrote BBC BASIC in ARM assembly language.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The in-depth knowledge gained from designing the instruction set enabled the code to be very dense, making ARM BBC BASIC an extremely good test for any ARM emulator.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] ARM Evaluations Systems featuring ARM1 CPUs and supplied as second processors for BBC Micro and Master machines, were made available from July 1986 under the Acorn OEM Products brand to developers and researchers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The A500 Second Processor, an additional ARM1 based BBC Micro and Master second processor, featured the ARM support chipset (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), was capable of producing video output and operating near independently of the host BBC Micro.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The result of the simulations on the ARM1 boards led to the late 1986 introduction of the ARM2 design running at 8 MHz, and the early 1987 speed-bumped version at 10 to 12 MHz.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] A significant change in the underlying architecture was the addition of a Booth multiplier, whereas formerly multiplication had to be carried out in software.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Further, a new Fast Interrupt reQuest mode, FIQ for short, allowed registers 8 to 14 to be replaced as part of the interrupt itself.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This meant FIQ requests did not have to save out their registers, further speeding interrupts.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The first use of the ARM2 was in internal Acorn A500 development machines, and the Acorn Archimedes personal computer models A305, A310, and A440, launched on the 6th June 1987.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] According to the Dhrystone benchmark, the ARM2 was roughly seven times the performance of a typical 7 MHz 68000-based system like the Amiga or Macintosh SE.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] It was twice as fast as an Intel 80386 running at 16 MHz, and about the same speed as a multi-processor VAX-11/784 superminicomputer.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The only systems that beat it were the Sun SPARC and MIPS R2000 RISC-based workstations.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Further, as the CPU was designed for high-speed I/O, it dispensed with many of the support chips seen in these machines; notably, it lacked any dedicated direct memory access (DMA) controller which was often found on workstations.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The graphics system was also simplified based on the same set of underlying assumptions about memory and timing.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The result was a dramatically simplified design, offering performance on par with expensive workstations but at a price point similar to contemporary desktops.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The ARM2 featured a 32-bit data bus, 26-bit address space and 27 32-bit registers, of which 16 are accessible at any one time (including the PC).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The ARM2 had a transistor count of just 30,000, compared to Motorola's six-year-older 68000 model with around 68,000.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Much of this simplicity came from the lack of microcode, which represents about one-quarter to one-third of the 68000's transistors, and the lack of (like most CPUs of the day) a cache.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This simplicity enabled the ARM2 to have a low power consumption and simpler thermal packaging by having fewer powered transistors.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Nevertheless, ARM2 offered better performance than the contemporary 1987 IBM PS/2 Model 50, which initially utilised an Intel 80286, offering 1.8 MIPS @ 10 MHz, and later in 1987, the 2 MIPS of the PS/2 70, with its Intel 386 DX @ 16 MHz.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] A successor, ARM3, was produced with a 4 KB cache, which further improved performance.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The address bus was extended to 32 bits in the ARM6, but program code still had to lie within the first 64 MB of memory in 26-bit compatibility mode, due to the reserved bits for the status flags.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In 1988, Sanyo became a worldwide second source for the ARM2 and associated chipset under an agreement with VLSI Technology.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In the late 1980s, Apple Computer and VLSI Technology started working with Acorn on newer versions of the ARM core.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In 1990, Acorn spun off the design team into a new company named Advanced RISC Machines Ltd., which became ARM Ltd. when its parent company, Arm Holdings plc, floated on the London Stock Exchange and Nasdaq in 1998.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The new Apple–ARM work would eventually evolve into the ARM6, first released in early 1992.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Apple used the ARM6-based ARM610 as the basis for their Apple Newton PDA.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In 1994, Acorn used the ARM610 as the main central processing unit (CPU) in their RiscPC computers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] DEC licensed the ARMv4 architecture and produced the StrongARM.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] At 233 MHz, this CPU drew only one watt (newer versions draw far less).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This work was later passed to Intel as part of a lawsuit settlement, and Intel took the opportunity to supplement their i960 line with the StrongARM.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Intel later developed its own high performance implementation named XScale, which it has since sold to Marvell.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Transistor count of the ARM core remained essentially the same throughout these changes; ARM2 had 30,000 transistors, while ARM6 grew only to 35,000.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In 2005, about 98% of all mobile phones sold used at least one ARM processor.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In 2010, producers of chips based on ARM architectures reported shipments of 6.1 billion ARM-based processors, representing 95% of smartphones, 35% of digital televisions and set-top boxes, and 10% of mobile computers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In 2011, the 32-bit ARM architecture was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices and the most popular 32-bit one in embedded systems.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In 2013, 10 billion were produced and "ARM-based chips are found in nearly 60 percent of the world's mobile devices".
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Arm Holdings's primary business is selling IP cores, which licensees use to create microcontrollers (MCUs), CPUs, and systems-on-chips based on those cores.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The original design manufacturer combines the ARM core with other parts to produce a complete device, typically one that can be built in existing semiconductor fabrication plants (fabs) at low cost and still deliver substantial performance.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The most successful implementation has been the ARM7TDMI with hundreds of millions sold.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Atmel has been a precursor design center in the ARM7TDMI-based embedded system.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] The ARM architectures used in smartphones, PDAs and other mobile devices range from ARMv5 to ARMv8-A.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In 2009, some manufacturers introduced netbooks based on ARM architecture CPUs, in direct competition with netbooks based on Intel Atom.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Arm Holdings offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Arm Holdings provides to all licensees an integratable hardware description of the ARM core as well as complete software development toolset (compiler, debugger, software development kit), and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] SoC packages integrating ARM's core designs include Nvidia Tegra's first three generations, CSR plc's Quatro family, ST-Ericsson's Nova and NovaThor, Silicon Labs's Precision32 MCU, Texas Instruments's OMAP products, Samsung's Hummingbird and Exynos products, Apple's A4, A5, and A5X, and NXP's i.MX.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Fabless licensees, who wish to integrate an ARM core into their own chip design, are usually only interested in acquiring a ready-to-manufacture verified semiconductor intellectual property core.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] For these customers, Arm Holdings delivers a gate netlist description of the chosen ARM core, along with an abstracted simulation model and test programs to aid design integration and verification.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] More ambitious customers, including integrated device manufacturers (IDM) and foundry operators, choose to acquire the processor IP in synthesizable RTL (Verilog) form.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] With the synthesizable RTL, the customer has the ability to perform architectural level optimisations and extensions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This allows the designer to achieve exotic design goals not otherwise possible with an unmodified netlist (high clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions, etc.).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] While Arm Holdings does not grant the licensee the right to resell the ARM architecture itself, licensees may freely sell manufactured products such as chip devices, evaluation boards and complete systems.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Merchant foundries can be a special case; not only are they allowed to sell finished silicon containing ARM cores, they generally hold the right to re-manufacture ARM cores for other customers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Arm Holdings prices its IP based on perceived value.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Lower performing ARM cores typically have lower licence costs than higher performing cores.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In implementation terms, a synthesisable core costs more than a hard macro (blackbox) core.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Complicating price matters, a merchant foundry that holds an ARM licence, such as Samsung or Fujitsu, can offer fab customers reduced licensing costs.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In exchange for acquiring the ARM core through the foundry's in-house design services, the customer can reduce or eliminate payment of ARM's upfront licence fee.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Compared to dedicated semiconductor foundries (such as TSMC and UMC) without in-house design services, Fujitsu/Samsung charge two- to three-times more per manufactured wafer.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] For low to mid volume applications, a design service foundry offers lower overall pricing (through subsidisation of the licence fee).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] For high volume mass-produced parts, the long term cost reduction achievable through lower wafer pricing reduces the impact of ARM's NRE (non-recurring engineering) costs, making the dedicated foundry a better choice.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In February 2016, ARM announced the Built on ARM Cortex Technology licence, often shortened to Built on Cortex (BoC) licence.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This licence allows companies to partner with ARM and make modifications to ARM Cortex designs.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] These design modifications will not be shared with other companies.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] These semi-custom core designs also have brand freedom, for example Kryo 280.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Companies that are current licensees of Built on ARM Cortex Technology include Qualcomm.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Companies can also obtain an ARM *architectural licence* for designing their own CPU cores using the ARM instruction sets.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] These cores must comply fully with the ARM architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Companies that have designed cores that implement an ARM architecture include Apple, AppliedMicro (now: Ampere Computing), Broadcom, Cavium (now: Marvell), Digital Equipment Corporation, Intel, Nvidia, Qualcomm, Samsung Electronics, Fujitsu, and NUVIA Inc.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] On 16 July 2019, ARM announced ARM Flexible Access.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] ARM Flexible Access provides unlimited access to included ARM intellectual property (IP) for development.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Per product licence fees are required once a customer reaches foundry tapeout or prototyping.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] 75% of ARM's most recent IP over the last two years are included in ARM Flexible Access.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] ARMv3 included a compatibility mode to support the 26-bit addresses of earlier versions of the architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] This compatibility mode is *optional* in ARMv4, and removed entirely in ARMv5.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Arm provides a list of vendors who implement ARM cores in their design (application specific standard products (ASSP), microprocessor and microcontrollers).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] ARM cores are used in a number of products, particularly PDAs and smartphones.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Some computing examples are Microsoft's first generation Surface, Surface 2 and Pocket PC devices (following 2002), Apple's iPads, and Asus's Eee Pad Transformer tablet computers, and several Chromebook laptops.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] Others include Apple's iPhone smartphones and iPod portable media players, Canon PowerShot digital cameras, Nintendo Switch hybrid, the Wii security processor and 3DS handheld game consoles, and TomTom turn-by-turn navigation systems.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] In 2005, Arm took part in the development of Manchester University's computer SpiNNaker, which used ARM cores to simulate the human brain.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p01] ARM chips are also used in Raspberry Pi, BeagleBoard, BeagleBone, PandaBoard, and other single-board computers, because they are very small, inexpensive, and consume very little power.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The 32-bit ARM architecture (**ARM32**), such as **ARMv7-A** (implementing AArch32; see section on Armv8-A for more on it), was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices as of 2011.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Although the architecture profiles were first defined for ARMv7, ARM subsequently defined the ARMv6-M architecture (used by the Cortex M0/M0+/M1) as a subset of the ARMv7-M profile with fewer instructions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] 26-bit addressing - obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Multiply and multiply-accumulate instructions; coprocessor support - all variants obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] 32-bit addressing - all variants obsolete as of July 2005.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] , the former of which supports the 32-bit ARM instruction set, called A32, and the Thumb-2 instruction set, called T32, and the latter of which supports a new instruction set with 32 64-bit registers, called A64.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Except in the M-profile, the 32-bit ARM architecture specifies several CPU modes, depending on the implemented architecture features.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] At any moment in time, the CPU can be in only one mode, but it can switch modes due to external events (interrupts) or programmatically.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The original ARM implementation was hardwired without microcode, like the much simpler 8-bit 6502 processor used in prior Acorn microcomputers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] ARM includes integer arithmetic operations for add, subtract, and multiply; some versions of the architecture also support divide operations.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] ARM supports 32-bit × 32-bit multiplies with either a 32-bit result or 64-bit result, though Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 cores do not support 64-bit results.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Some ARM cores also support 16-bit × 16-bit and 32-bit × 16-bit multiplies.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Registers R0 through R7 are the same across all CPU modes; they are never banked.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Registers R8 through R12 are the same across all CPU modes except FIQ mode.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] FIQ mode has its own distinct R8 through R12 registers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] R13 and R14 are banked across all privileged CPU modes except system mode.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] That is, each mode that can be entered because of an exception has its own R13 and R14.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] These registers generally contain the stack pointer and the return address from function calls, respectively.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Current Program Status Register (CPSR) has the following 32 bits.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Almost every ARM instruction has a conditional execution feature called predication, which is implemented with a 4-bit condition code selector (the predicate).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] To allow for unconditional execution, one of the four-bit codes causes the instruction to be always executed.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Most other CPU architectures only have condition codes on branch instructions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Though the predicate takes up four of the 32 bits in an instruction code, and thus cuts down significantly on the encoding bits available for displacements in memory access instructions, it avoids branch instructions when generating code for small `if` statements.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Apart from eliminating the branch instructions themselves, this preserves the fetch/decode/execute pipeline at the cost of only one cycle per skipped instruction.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] An algorithm that provides a good example of conditional execution is the subtraction-based Euclidean algorithm for computing the greatest common divisor.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] which avoids the branches around the `then` and `else` clauses.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] If `r0` and `r1` are equal then neither of the `SUB` instructions will be executed, eliminating the need for a conditional branch to implement the `while` check at the top of the loop, for example had `SUBLE` (less than or equal) been used.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] One of the ways that Thumb code provides a more dense encoding is to remove the four-bit selector from non-branch instructions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] This results in the typical ARM program being denser than expected with fewer memory accesses; thus the pipeline is used more efficiently.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The ARM processor also has features rarely seen in other RISC architectures, such as PC-relative addressing (indeed, on the 32-bit ARM the PC is one of its 16 registers) and pre- and post-increment addressing modes.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The ARM instruction set has increased over time.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Some early ARM processors (before ARM7TDMI), for example, have no instruction to store a two-byte quantity.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The ARM7 and earlier implementations have a three-stage pipeline; the stages being fetch, decode, and execute.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Higher-performance designs, such as the ARM9, have deeper pipelines: Cortex-A8 has thirteen stages.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Additional implementation changes for higher performance include a faster adder and more extensive branch prediction logic.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The difference between the ARM7DI and ARM7DMI cores, for example, was an improved multiplier; hence the added "M".
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The ARM architecture (pre-Armv8) provides a non-intrusive way of extending the instruction set using "coprocessors" that can be addressed using MCR, MRC, MRRC, MCRR, and similar instructions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The coprocessor space is divided logically into 16 coprocessors with numbers from 0 to 15, coprocessor 15 (cp15) being reserved for some typical control functions like managing the caches and MMU operation on processors that have one.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In ARM-based machines, peripheral devices are usually attached to the processor by mapping their physical registers into ARM memory space, into the coprocessor space, or by connecting to another device (a bus) that in turn attaches to the processor.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Coprocessor accesses have lower latency, so some peripherals—for example, an XScale interrupt controller—are accessible in both ways: through memory and through coprocessors.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In other cases, chip designers only integrate hardware using the coprocessor mechanism.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] For example, an image processing engine might be a small ARM7TDMI core combined with a coprocessor that has specialised operations to support a specific set of HDTV transcoding primitives.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] All modern ARM processors include hardware debugging facilities, allowing software debuggers to perform operations such as halting, stepping, and breakpointing of code starting from reset.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] These facilities are built using JTAG support, though some newer cores optionally support ARM's own two-wire "SWD" protocol.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In ARM7TDMI cores, the "D" represented JTAG debug support, and the "I" represented presence of an "EmbeddedICE" debug module.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] For ARM7 and ARM9 core generations, EmbeddedICE over JTAG was a de facto debug standard, though not architecturally guaranteed.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The ARMv7 architecture defines basic debug facilities at an architectural level.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] These include breakpoints, watchpoints and instruction execution in a "Debug Mode"; similar facilities were also available with EmbeddedICE.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Both "halt mode" and "monitor" mode debugging are supported.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The actual transport mechanism used to access the debug facilities is not architecturally specified, but implementations generally include JTAG support.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] There is a separate ARM "CoreSight" debug architecture, which is not architecturally required by ARMv7 processors.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Debug Access Port (DAP) is an implementation of an ARM Debug Interface.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] There are two different supported implementations, the Serial Wire JTAG Debug Port (SWJ-DP) and the Serial Wire Debug Port (SW-DP).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] CMSIS-DAP is a standard interface that describes how various debugging software on a host PC can communicate over USB to firmware running on a hardware debugger, which in turn talks over SWD or JTAG to a CoreSight-enabled ARM Cortex CPU.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] To improve the ARM architecture for digital signal processing and multimedia applications, DSP instructions were added to the instruction set.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] These are signified by an "E" in the name of the ARMv5TE and ARMv5TEJ architectures.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The new instructions are common in digital signal processor (DSP) architectures.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] They include variations on signed multiply–accumulate, saturated add and subtract, and count leading zeros.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] First introduced in 1999, this extension of the core instruction set contrasted with ARM's earlier DSP coprocessor known as Piccolo, which employed a distinct, incompatible instruction set whose execution involved a separate program counter.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Piccolo instructions employed a distinct register file of sixteen 32-bit registers, with some instructions combining registers for use as 48-bit accumulators and other instructions addressing 16-bit half-registers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Some instructions were able to operate on two such 16-bit values in parallel.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Communication with the Piccolo register file involved *load to Piccolo* and *store from Piccolo* coprocessor instructions via two buffers of eight 32-bit entries.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Described as reminiscent of other approaches, notably Hitachi's SH-DSP and Motorola's 68356, Piccolo did not employ dedicated local memory and relied on the bandwidth of the ARM core for DSP operand retrieval, impacting concurrent performance.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Piccolo's distinct instruction set also proved not to be a "good compiler target".
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Introduced in the ARMv6 architecture, this was a precursor to Advanced SIMD, also named Neon.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Jazelle DBX (Direct Bytecode eXecution) is a technique that allows Java bytecode to be executed directly in the ARM architecture as a third execution state (and instruction set) alongside the existing ARM and Thumb-mode.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Support for this state is signified by the "J" in the ARMv5TEJ architecture, and in ARM9EJ-S and ARM7EJ-S core names.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Support for this state is required starting in ARMv6 (except for the ARMv7-M profile), though newer cores only include a trivial implementation that provides no hardware acceleration.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] To improve compiled code density, processors since the ARM7TDMI (released in 1994) have featured the *Thumb* compressed instruction set, which have their own state.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] (The "T" in "TDMI" indicates the Thumb feature.) When in this state, the processor executes the Thumb instruction set, a compact 16-bit encoding for a subset of the ARM instruction set.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Most of the Thumb instructions are directly mapped to normal ARM instructions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The space saving comes from making some of the instruction operands implicit and limiting the number of possibilities compared to the ARM instructions executed in the ARM instruction set state.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In Thumb, the 16-bit opcodes have less functionality.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] For example, only branches can be conditional, and many opcodes are restricted to accessing only half of all of the CPU's general-purpose registers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The shorter opcodes give improved code density overall, even though some operations require extra instructions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In situations where the memory port or bus width is constrained to less than 32 bits, the shorter Thumb opcodes allow increased performance compared with 32-bit ARM code, as less program code may need to be loaded into the processor over the constrained memory bandwidth.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Unlike processor architectures with variable length (16- or 32-bit) instructions, such as the Cray-1 and Hitachi SuperH, the ARM and Thumb instruction sets exist independently of each other.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Embedded hardware, such as the Game Boy Advance, typically have a small amount of RAM accessible with a full 32-bit datapath; the majority is accessed via a 16-bit or narrower secondary datapath.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In this situation, it usually makes sense to compile Thumb code and hand-optimise a few of the most CPU-intensive sections using full 32-bit ARM instructions, placing these wider instructions into the 32-bit bus accessible memory.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The first processor with a Thumb instruction decoder was the ARM7TDMI.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] All processors supporting 32-bit instruction sets, starting with ARM9, and including XScale, have included a Thumb instruction decoder.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It includes instructions adopted from the Hitachi SuperH (1992), which was licensed by ARM.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] ARM's smallest processor families (Cortex M0 and M1) implement only the 16-bit Thumb instruction set for maximum performance in lowest cost applications.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] ARM processors that don't support 32-bit addressing also omit Thumb.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Thumb-2 extends the Thumb instruction set with bit-field manipulation, table branches and conditional execution.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] At the same time, the ARM instruction set was extended to maintain equivalent functionality in both instruction sets.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] A new "Unified Assembly Language" (UAL) supports generation of either Thumb or ARM instructions from the same source code; versions of Thumb seen on ARMv7 processors are essentially as capable as ARM code (including the ability to write interrupt handlers).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] This requires a bit of care, and use of a new "IT" (if-then) instruction, which permits up to four successive instructions to execute based on a tested condition, or on its inverse.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] When compiling into ARM code, this is ignored, but when compiling into Thumb it generates an actual instruction.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] All ARMv7 chips support the Thumb instruction set.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] All chips in the Cortex-A series that support ARMv7, all Cortex-R series, and all ARM11 series support both "ARM instruction set state" and "Thumb instruction set state", while chips in the Cortex-M series support only the Thumb instruction set.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] New features provided by ThumbEE include automatic null pointer checks on every load and store instruction, an instruction to perform an array bounds check, and special instructions that call a handler.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In addition, because it utilises Thumb-2 technology, ThumbEE provides access to registers r8–r15 (where the Jazelle/DBX Java VM state is held).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Handlers are small sections of frequently called code, commonly used to implement high level languages, such as allocating memory for a new object.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] These changes come from repurposing a handful of opcodes, and knowing the core is in the new ThumbEE state.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] On 23 November 2011, Arm deprecated any use of the ThumbEE instruction set, and Armv8 removes support for ThumbEE.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Some devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 have a cut-down *VFPLite* module instead of a full VFP module, and require roughly ten times more clock cycles per float operation.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Pre-Armv8 architecture implemented floating-point/SIMD with the coprocessor interface.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Other floating-point and/or SIMD units found in ARM-based processors using the coprocessor interface include FPA, FPE, iwMMXt, some of which were implemented in software by trapping but could have been implemented in hardware.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] They provide some of the same functionality as VFP but are not opcode-compatible with it.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] FPA10 also provides extended precision, but implements correct rounding (required by IEEE 754) only in single precision.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] An optional extension to the ARM instruction set in the ARMv5TE, ARMv5TEJ and ARMv6 architectures.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Implemented on most Cortex-A8 and A9 ARMv7 processors.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It is backward-compatible with VFPv2, except that it cannot trap floating-point exceptions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] VFPv3 has 32 64-bit FPU registers as standard, adds VCVT instructions to convert between scalar, float and double, adds immediate mode to VMOV such that constants can be loaded into FPU registers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] As above, but with only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A12 and A15 ARMv7 processors, Cortex-A7 optionally has VFPv4-D32 in the case of an FPU with Neon.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] As above, but it has only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A5 and A7 processors in the case of an FPU without Neon.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Implemented on Cortex-M7 when single and double-precision floating-point core option exists.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In Debian Linux and derivatives such as Ubuntu and Linux Mint, **armhf** (**ARM hard float**) refers to the ARMv7 architecture including the additional VFP3-D16 floating-point hardware extension (and Thumb-2) above.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Software packages and cross-compiler tools use the armhf vs. arm/armel suffixes to differentiate.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The *Advanced SIMD* extension (also known as *Neon* or "MPE" Media Processing Engine) is a combined 64- and 128-bit SIMD instruction set that provides standardised acceleration for media and signal processing applications.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Neon is included in all Cortex-A8 devices, but is optional in Cortex-A9 devices.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Neon can execute MP3 audio decoding on CPUs running at 10 MHz, and can run the GSM adaptive multi-rate (AMR) speech codec at 13 MHz.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It features a comprehensive instruction set, separate register files, and independent execution hardware.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Neon supports 8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit integer and single-precision (32-bit) floating-point data and SIMD operations for handling audio and video processing as well as graphics and gaming processing.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In Neon, the SIMD supports up to 16 operations at the same time.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Neon hardware shares the same floating-point registers as used in VFP.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 and Cortex-A9 support 128-bit vectors, but will execute with 64 bits at a time, whereas some more powerful CPUs such as Cortex-A15 can execute 128 bits at a time.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] A quirk of Neon in Armv7 devices is that it flushes all subnormal numbers to zero, and as a result the GCC compiler will not use it unless `-funsafe-math-optimizations`, which allows losing denormals, is turned on.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] "Enhanced" Neon defined since Armv8 does not have this quirk, but as of GCC 8.2 the same flag is still required to enable Neon instructions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] On the other hand, GCC does consider Neon safe on AArch64 for Armv8.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] ProjectNe10 is ARM's first open-source project (from its inception; while they acquired an older project, now named Mbed TLS).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Ne10 library is a set of common, useful functions written in both Neon and C (for compatibility).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The library was created to allow developers to use Neon optimisations without learning Neon, but it also serves as a set of highly optimised Neon intrinsic and assembly code examples for common DSP, arithmetic, and image processing routines.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Helium is the M-Profile Vector Extension (MVE).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It adds more than 150 scalar and vector instructions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Security Extensions, marketed as TrustZone Technology, is in ARMv6KZ and later application profile architectures.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It provides a low-cost alternative to adding another dedicated security core to an SoC, by providing two virtual processors backed by hardware based access control.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] This lets the application core switch between two states, referred to as *worlds* (to reduce confusion with other names for capability domains), to prevent information leaking from the more trusted world (the *Secure world*) to the less trusted world (the *Normal world*).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] This world switch is generally orthogonal to all other capabilities of the processor, thus each world can operate independently of the other while using the same core.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Memory and peripherals are then made aware of the operating world of the core and may use this to provide access control to secrets and code on the device.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Typically, a rich operating system is run in the less trusted world, with smaller security-specialised code in the more trusted world, aiming to reduce the attack surface.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Typical applications include DRM functionality for controlling the use of media on ARM-based devices, and preventing any unapproved use of the device.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In practice, since the specific implementation details of proprietary TrustZone implementations have not been publicly disclosed for review, it is unclear what level of assurance is provided for a given threat model, but they are not immune from attack.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Open Virtualization is an open source implementation of the trusted world architecture for TrustZone.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] AMD has licensed and incorporated TrustZone technology into its Secure Processor Technology.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] AMD's APUs include a Cortex-A5 processor for handling secure processing, which is enabled in some, but not all products.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In fact, the Cortex-A5 TrustZone core had been included in earlier AMD products, but was not enabled due to time constraints.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Samsung Knox uses TrustZone for purposes such as detecting modifications to the kernel, storing certificates and attestating keys.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Security Extension, marketed as TrustZone for Armv8-M Technology, was introduced in the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] While containing similar concepts to TrustZone for Armv8-A, it has a different architectural design, as world switching is performed using branch instructions instead of using exceptions.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It also supports safe interleaved interrupt handling from either world regardless of the current security state.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Together these features provide low latency calls to the secure world and responsive interrupt handling.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] ARM provides a reference stack of secure world code in the form of Trusted Firmware for M and PSA Certified.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] As of ARMv6, the ARM architecture supports no-execute page protection, which is referred to as *XN*, for *eXecute Never*.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Large Physical Address Extension (LPAE), which extends the physical address size from 32 bits to 40 bits, was added to the Armv7-A architecture in 2011.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The physical address size may be even larger in processors based on the 64-bit (Armv8-A) architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] For example, it is 44 bits in Cortex-A75 and Cortex-A65AE.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The **Armv8-R** and **Armv8-M** architectures, announced after the Armv8-A architecture, share some features with Armv8-A.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] However, Armv8-M does not include any 64-bit AArch64 instructions, and Armv8-R originally did not include any AArch64 instructions; those instructions were added to Armv8-R later.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Armv8.1-M architecture, announced in February 2019, is an enhancement of the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Announced in October 2011, **Armv8-A** (often called ARMv8 while the Armv8-R is also available) represents a fundamental change to the ARM architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It supports two *Execution states*: a 64-bit state named *AArch64* and a 32-bit state named *AArch32*.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] In the AArch64 state, a new 64-bit *A64* instruction set is supported; in the AArch32 state, two instruction sets are supported: the original 32-bit instruction set, named *A32*, and the 32-bit Thumb-2 instruction set, named *T32*.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] AArch32 provides user-space compatibility with Armv7-A.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The processor state can change on an Exception level change; this allows 32-bit applications to be executed in AArch32 state under a 64-bit OS whose kernel executes in AArch64 state, and allows a 32-bit OS to run in AArch32 state under the control of a 64-bit hypervisor running in AArch64 state.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] ARM announced their Cortex-A53 and Cortex-A57 cores on 30 October 2012.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Apple was the first to release an Armv8-A compatible core in a consumer product (Apple A7 in iPhone 5S).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] AppliedMicro, using an FPGA, was the first to demo Armv8-A.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The first Armv8-A SoC from Samsung is the Exynos 5433 used in the Galaxy Note 4, which features two clusters of four Cortex-A57 and Cortex-A53 cores in a big.LITTLE configuration; but it will run only in AArch32 mode.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] To both AArch32 and AArch64, Armv8-A makes VFPv3/v4 and advanced SIMD (Neon) standard.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It also adds cryptography instructions supporting AES, SHA-1/SHA-256 and finite field arithmetic.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] AArch64 was introduced in Armv8-A and its subsequent revision.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] AArch64 is not included in the 32-bit Armv8-R and Armv8-M architectures.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] An ARMv8-A processor can support one or both of AArch32 and AArch64; it may support AArch32 and AArch64 at lower Exception levels and only AArch64 at higher Exception levels.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] For example, the ARM Cortex-A32 supports only AArch32, the ARM Cortex-A34 supports only AArch64, and the ARM Cortex-A72 supports both AArch64 and AArch32.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] An ARMv9-A processor must support AArch64 at all Exception levels, and may support AArch32 at EL0.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Optional AArch64 support was added to the Armv8-R profile, with the first ARM core implementing it being the Cortex-R82.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Announced in March 2021, the updated architecture places a focus on secure execution and compartmentalisation.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The first ARMv9-A processors were released later that year, including the Cortex-A510, Cortex-A710 and Cortex-X2.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Arm SystemReady is a compliance program that helps ensure the interoperability of an operating system on Arm-based hardware from datacenter servers to industrial edge and IoT devices.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The key building blocks of the program are the specifications for minimum hardware and firmware requirements that the operating systems and hypervisors can rely upon.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] These specifications are co-developed by Arm and its partners in the System Architecture Advisory Committee (SystemArchAC).
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Architecture Compliance Suite (ACS) is the test tools that help to check the compliance of these specifications.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Arm SystemReady Requirements Specification documents the requirements of the certifications.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] This program was introduced by Arm in 2020 at the first DevSummit event.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Its predecessor Arm ServerReady was introduced in 2018 at the Arm TechCon event.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] PSA Certified, formerly named Platform Security Architecture, is an architecture-agnostic security framework and evaluation scheme.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It is intended to help secure Internet of things (IoT) devices built on system-on-a-chip (SoC) processors.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It was introduced to increase security where a full trusted execution environment is too large or complex.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The architecture was introduced by Arm in 2017 at the annual TechCon event.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Although the scheme is architecture agnostic, it was first implemented on Arm Cortex-M processor cores intended for microcontroller use.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] PSA Certified includes freely available threat models and security analyses that demonstrate the process for deciding on security features in common IoT products.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] It also provides freely downloadable application programming interface (API) packages, architectural specifications, open-source firmware implementations, and related test suites.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Following the development of the architecture security framework in 2017, the PSA Certified assurance scheme launched two years later at Embedded World in 2019.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] PSA Certified offers a multi-level security evaluation scheme for chip vendors, OS providers and IoT device makers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The Embedded World presentation introduced chip vendors to Level 1 Certification.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] A draft of Level 2 protection was presented at the same time.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Level 2 certification became a usable standard in February 2020.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The certification was created by PSA Joint Stakeholders to enable a security-by-design approach for a diverse set of IoT products.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] PSA Certified specifications are implementation and architecture agnostic, as a result they can be applied to any chip, software or device.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The certification also removes industry fragmentation for IoT product manufacturers and developers.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The first 32-bit ARM-based personal computer, the Acorn Archimedes, was originally intended to run an ambitious operating system called ARX.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] The machines shipped with RISC OS, which was also used on later ARM-based systems from Acorn and other vendors.
[src:bootloader-security/arm-trustzone-p02] Some early Acorn machines were also able to run a Unix port called RISC iX.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Upon power up, hardware usually starts uninitialized.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] To continue booting, the system may need to read a bootloader from some peripheral device, usually a data storage device.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] It is often easier to implement routines for reading from external storage devices in software than in hardware.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] A boot ROM provides a place to store this initial loading code, at a fixed location immediately available to the processor when execution starts.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The boot ROM is mapped into memory at a fixed location, and the processor is designed to start executing from this location after reset, according to the processor's reset vector.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The boot ROM is either placed on the same die as the CPU or is an external ROM chip.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] On modern systems, the boot ROM (whether integrated into CPU or external ROM chip) usually uses NOR flash, which supports execute in place.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The boot ROM will then initialize the hardware busses and peripherals needed to boot.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] In some cases, the boot ROM is capable of initializing DRAM, and in other cases it is up to the bootloader to do that.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] On some modern ARM CPUs, the boot ROM integrated in CPU will initialize DRAM and then load a bootloader; but after a bootloader (such as Das U-Boot) is loaded, the bootloader may reinitialize DRAM, to fix bugs and reduce cost.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] In many systems on a chip (SoC), the peripherals or buses from which the boot ROM tries to load the bootloader, and the order in which they are loaded, can be configured.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] This configuration can be done by blowing some electronic fuses inside the system on a chip to encode that information, or by having specific pins or jumpers of the system on a chip high or low.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Some boot ROMs are capable of checking the digital signature of the bootloader and will refuse to run the bootloader and stop the boot if the signature is not valid or has not been signed with an authorized key.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] With some boot ROMs, the hash of the public key needed to verify the signatures is encoded in OTP electronic fuses inside the SoC.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] That feature can then be used to implement security features or used as a hardware root of trust in a chain of trust, but once configured, users are denied the freedom to replace the bootloader with the one they want without the use of boot ROM exploits.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Because of this, the feature has raised strong concerns from the free software community.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Just before jumping to the bootloader, some systems on a chip also remove the boot ROM from the memory mapping, while others do not, making it possible to dump the boot ROM for later analysis.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] If the boot ROM is still accessible, bootloaders can also call the code of the boot ROM (which is sometimes documented).
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] When a system on a chip (SoC) enters suspend-to-RAM mode, in many cases, the processor is completely off while the RAM is put in self-refresh mode.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] At resume, the boot ROM is executed again and many boot ROMs are able to detect that the SoC was in suspend-to-RAM mode and can resume by jumping directly to the kernel which then takes care of powering on again the peripherals which were off and restoring the state that the computer was in before.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] On many Allwinner systems on a chip (A10, A20, A64), the boot ROM either waits for a bootloader to be loaded through USB (if a specific PIN is high) or tries to boot on several peripherals in a fixed order.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Some Allwinner systems on a chip can verify the signature of the booloaders.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] But most devices being manufactured are not configured for that.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] This has enabled free and open-source software to add support for many Allwinner systems on a chip and devices using them in bootloaders like U-Boot.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] On iPhone, iPad, Apple Watch, iPod Touch, and Apple TV devices, the boot ROM is called "SecureROM" It is a stripped-down version of iBoot.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] It provides a Device Firmware Upgrade (DFU) mechanism, which can be activated using a special button combination.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] On older IBM PC compatible computers, the BIOS serves as a boot ROM.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The boot ROM of NXP systems on a chip (SOCs) support configuring the peripherals through specific pins of the system on a chip.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] On the i.MX6 family it also supports configuring the boot order through eFuses.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The boot ROM of several NXP SoCs have many ways to load the first stage bootloader (from eMMC, microSD, USB, etc.).
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Several NXP SoCs can be configured to verify the signature of the bootloaders.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Many devices with such SoCs were sold without that verification configured and on those devices users can install the bootloader they want, including several free and open-source software bootloaders like Das U-Boot and Barebox.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Open Firmware serves as a boot ROM in systems such as later SPARC-based machines from Sun Microsystems and PowerPC-based Macs.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] STMicroelectronics STM32 family microcontrollers have embedded ROM (also referred as "on-chip ROM") called *system memory* to facilitate empty system flashing.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Certain pin combinations or sometimes efuses and/or empty flash checks force the chip to boot from ROM instead of the firmware in main flash.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] This allows empty chips to be flashed without resorting to hardware programming interfaces.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Technically this ROM is stored in a dedicated area of the flash array and programmed by ST during production.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Most STM32 microcontrollers can at least be flashed over UART, some support USB and eventually other interfaces like e.g.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The Cortex-M core normally fetches vectors from the well-known addresses 0x00000000 (initial stack pointer value) and 0x00000004 (initial program counter value).
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] However pins and/or fuses define which memory is mapped at these addresses.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] System memory is one of the mapping options, another would typically be main firmware in flash.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] In this case, firmware is supposed to do all the jobs boot ROMs do; part of the firmware could act as a bootloader similar to ST's boot ROM.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Hardware could provide read-only enforcement on the boot area, turning it into a user-provided version of boot ROM.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The boot ROMs of several Texas Instruments systems on a chip support configuring the peripherals through specific pins of the system on a chip.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] On the OMAP36xx system on a chip, the boot ROM looks for the first stage bootloader at the sectors 0x0 and 0x20000 (128KB), and on the AM3358 system on a chip, it additionally looks at 0x40000 (256KiB) and 0x60000 (384KiB).
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] In both cases its maximum size is 128KiB.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] This is because the (first stage) bootloader is loaded in an SRAM that is inside the system on a chip.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The OMAP and AM335x systems on a chip can be configured to verify the signature of the bootloaders.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] Many devices with such system on a chip were sold without verification configured and on those devices users can install the bootloader they want, including several free and open-source software bootloaders like Das U-Boot and Coreboot and Barebox.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] UEFI serves as a boot ROM on systems such as newer IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] On devices running iOS, boot ROM exploits (like the limera1n, alloc8, and checkm8 exploits) are sometimes used for iOS jailbreaking.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The advantage for people wanting to jailbreak their devices over exploits that affect iOS is that since the boot ROM cannot be modified—and that devices running iOS do not have fuses to append code to the boot ROM, Apple cannot fix the vulnerability on existing devices.
[src:bootloader-security/boot-rom] The boot ROM of the Tegra SoC of Nvidia (used by the Nintendo Switch) contained a vulnerability which made it possible for users to run the bootloader they want.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] In computer security, a **chain of trust** is established by validating each component of hardware and software from the end entity up to the root certificate.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] It is intended to ensure that only trusted software and hardware can be used while still retaining flexibility.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] A chain of trust is designed to allow multiple users to create and use the software on the system, which would be more difficult if all the keys were stored directly in hardware.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] It starts with hardware that will only boot from software that is digitally signed (bootloader).
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] The signing authority will only sign boot programs that enforce security, such as only running programs that are themselves signed, or only allowing signed code to have access to certain features of the machine.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] This process may continue for several layers.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] This process results in a chain of trust.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] The final software can be trusted to have certain properties because if it had been illegally modified its signature would be invalid, and the previous software would not have executed it.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] The previous software can be trusted, because it, in turn, would not have been loaded if its signature had been invalid.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] The trustworthiness of each layer is guaranteed by the one before, back to the trust anchor.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] It would be possible to have the hardware check the suitability (signature) for every single piece of software.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] However, this would not produce the flexibility that a "chain" provides.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] In a chain, any given link can be replaced with a different version to provide different properties, without having to go all the way back to the trust anchor.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] This use of multiple layers is an application of a general technique to improve scalability and is analogous to the use of multiple certificates in a certificate chain.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] In computer security, digital certificates are verified using a chain of trust.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] The trust anchor for the digital certificate is the root certificate authority (CA).
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] The certificate hierarchy is a structure of certificates that allows individuals to verify the validity of a certificate's issuer.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] Certificates are issued and signed by certificates that reside higher in the certificate hierarchy, so the validity and trustworthiness of a given certificate is determined by the corresponding validity of the certificate that signed it.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] The chain of trust of a certificate chain is an ordered list of certificates, containing an end-user subscriber certificate and intermediate certificates (that represents the intermediate CA), that enables the receiver to verify that the sender and all intermediate certificates are trustworthy.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] This process is best described in the page *Intermediate certificate authority*.
[src:bootloader-security/chain-of-trust] See also X.509 certificate chains for a description of these concepts in a widely used standard for digital certificates.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Code signing can provide several valuable features.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] The most common use of code signing is to provide security when deploying; in some programming languages, it can also be used to help prevent namespace conflicts.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Almost every code signing implementation will provide some sort of digital signature mechanism to verify the identity of the author or build system, and a checksum to verify that the object has not been modified.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] It can also be used to provide versioning information about an object or to store other metadata about an object.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] The efficacy of code signing as an authentication mechanism for software depends on the security of underpinning signing keys.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] As with other public key infrastructure (PKI) technologies, the integrity of the system relies on publishers securing their private keys against unauthorized access.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Keys stored in software on general-purpose computers are susceptible to compromise.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Therefore, it is more secure, and best practice, to store keys in secure, tamper-proof, cryptographic hardware devices known as hardware security modules or HSMs.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Many code signing implementations will provide a way to sign the code using a system involving a pair of keys, one public and one private, similar to the process employed by TLS or SSH.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] For example, in the case of .NET, the developer uses a private key to sign their libraries or executables each time they build.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] This key will be unique to a developer or group or sometimes per application or object.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] The developer can either generate this key on their own or obtain one from a trusted certificate authority (CA).
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Code signing is particularly valuable in distributed environments, where the source of a given piece of code may not be immediately evident - for example Java applets, ActiveX controls and other active web and browser scripting code.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Another important usage is to safely provide updates and patches to existing software.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Windows, Mac OS X, and most Linux distributions provide updates using code signing to ensure that it is not possible for others to maliciously distribute code via the patch system.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] It allows the receiving operating system to verify that the update is legitimate, even if the update was delivered by third parties or physical media (disks).
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Code signing is used on Windows and Mac OS X to authenticate software on first run, ensuring that the software has not been maliciously tampered with by a third-party distributor or download site.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Debian-based Linux distributions (among others) validate downloaded packages using public key cryptography.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] The public key used to authenticate the code signature should be traceable back to a trusted root authority CA, preferably using a secure public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] This does not ensure that the code itself can be trusted, only that it comes from the stated source (or more explicitly, from a particular private key).
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] A CA provides a root trust level and is able to assign trust to others by proxy.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] If a user trusts a CA, then the user can presumably trust the legitimacy of code that is signed with a key generated by that CA or one of its proxies.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Many operating systems and frameworks contain built-in trust for one or more certification authorities.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] It is also commonplace for large organizations to implement a private CA, internal to the organization, which provides the same features as public CAs, but it is only trusted within the organization.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Extended validation (EV) code signing certificates are subject to additional validation and technical requirements.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] These guidelines are based on the CA/B Forum's Baseline Requirements and Extended Validation Guidelines.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Certain applications, such as signing Windows 10 kernel-mode drivers, require an EV code signing certificate.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] This is an example of a decoded EV code signing certificate used by SSL.com to sign software.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] `SSL.com EV Code Signing Intermediate CA RSA R3` is shown as the Issuer's commonName, identifying this as an EV code signing certificate.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] The certificate's `Subject` field describes SSL Corp as an organization.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] `Code Signing` is shown as the sole X509v3 Extended Key Usage.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] The other model is the trust on first use model, in which developers can choose to provide their own self-generated key.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] In this scenario, the user would normally have to obtain the public key in some fashion directly from the developer to verify the object is from them for the first time.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Many code signing systems will store the public key inside the signature.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Some software frameworks and OSs that check the code's signature before executing will allow you to choose to trust that developer from that point on after the first run.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] An application developer can provide a similar system by including the public keys with the installer.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] The key can then be used to ensure that any subsequent objects that need to run, such as upgrades, plugins, or another application, are all verified as coming from that same developer.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Time-stamping was designed to circumvent the trust warning that will appear in the case of an expired certificate.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] In effect, time-stamping extends the code trust beyond the validity period of a certificate.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] In the event that a certificate has to be revoked due to a compromise, a specific date and time of the compromising event will become part of the revocation record.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] In this case, time-stamping helps establish whether the code was signed before or after the certificate was compromised.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Developers need to sign their iOS and tvOS apps before running them on any real device and before uploading them to the App Store.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] This is needed to prove that the developer owns a valid Apple Developer ID.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] An application needs a valid profile or certificate so that it can run on the devices.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Like any security measure, code signing can be defeated.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Users can be tricked into running unsigned code, or even into running code that refuses to validate, and the system only remains secure as long as the private key remains private.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] It is also important to note that code signing does not protect the end user from any malicious activity or unintentional software bugs by the software author — it merely ensures that the software has not been modified by anyone other than the author.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Sometimes, sandbox systems do not accept certificates, because of a false time-stamp or because of an excess usage of RAM.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Microsoft implements a form of code signing (based on Authenticode) provided for Microsoft tested drivers.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Since drivers run in the kernel, they can destabilize the system or open the system to security holes.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] For this reason, Microsoft tests drivers submitted to its WHQL program.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] After the driver has passed, Microsoft signs that version of the driver as being safe.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] On 32-bit systems only, installing drivers that are not validated with Microsoft is possible after agreeing to allow the installation at a prompt warning the user that the code is unsigned.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] For .NET (managed) code, there is an additional mechanism called Strong Name Signing that uses Public/Private keys and SHA-1 hash as opposed to certificates.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] However, Microsoft discourages reliance on Strong Name Signing as a replacement for Authenticode.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] The CAs subsequently issued announcements on compliance with the decision.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] In the context of consumer devices such as games consoles, the term "unsigned code" is often used to refer to an application which has not been signed with the cryptographic key normally required for software to be accepted and executed.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] Most console games have to be signed with a secret key designed by the console maker or the game will not load on the console (both to enforce Vendor lock-in and combat software piracy).
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] There are several methods to get unsigned code to execute which include software exploits, the use of a modchip, a technique known as the swap trick or running a softmod.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] It may not initially seem obvious why simply copying a signed application onto another DVD does not allow it to boot.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] On the Xbox, the reason for this is that the Xbox executable file (XBE) contains a media-type flag, which specifies the type of media that the XBE is bootable from.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] On nearly all Xbox software, this is set such that the executable will only boot from factory-produced discs, so simply copying the executable to burnable media is enough to stop the execution of the software.
[src:bootloader-security/code-signing] However, since the executable is signed, simply changing the value of the flag is not possible as this alters the signature of the executable, causing it to fail validation when checked.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI replaces the BIOS that was present in the boot ROM of all personal computers that are IBM PC compatible, although it can provide backwards compatibility with the BIOS using CSM booting.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Unlike the BIOS, which was originally developed by IBM as a proprietary architecture, the UEFI specification is managed by an industry consortium.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Most production firmware implementations for both remain proprietary.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Intel developed the original *Extensible Firmware Interface* (*EFI*) specification.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The last Intel version of EFI was 1.10 released in 2005.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Subsequent versions have been developed as UEFI by the UEFI Forum.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI is independent of platform and programming language, but C is used for the reference implementation TianoCore EDKII.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The original motivation for EFI came during early development of the first Intel–HP Itanium systems in the mid-1990s.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] BIOS limitations had become too restrictive for the larger server platforms for which Itanium was targeted.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The effort to address these concerns began in 1998 and was initially called *Intel Boot Initiative*.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] It was later renamed to *Extensible Firmware Interface* (EFI).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The first open-source UEFI implementation, Tiano, was released by Intel in 2004.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Tiano has since then been superseded by EDK and EDK II and is now maintained by the TianoCore community.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In July 2008, Intel ceased its development of the EFI specification at version 1.10 and contributed it to the Unified EFI Forum, which has developed the specification as the *Unified Extensible Firmware Interface* (UEFI).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The original EFI specification remains owned by Intel, which exclusively provides licenses for EFI-based products, but the UEFI specification is owned by the UEFI Forum.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Version 2.0 of the UEFI specification was released on 31 January 2006.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Version 2.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 7 January 2007.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] It added network authentication and the user interface architecture ("Human Interface Infrastructure" in UEFI).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Version 2.3.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 6 April 2011.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] It added Secure Boot, as well as ARM architecture support.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In October 2018, Arm introduced Arm ServerReady, a compliance certification program intended to ensure standard operating systems and hypervisors run on Arm-based servers.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The program requires the system firmware to comply with Server Base Boot Requirements (SBBR).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] SBBR requires UEFI, ACPI and SMBIOS compliance.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In October 2020, Arm announced the extension of the program to the edge and IoT market.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The new program name is Arm SystemReady.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Many Linux and BSD distributions can support both recipes.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In December 2018, Microsoft announced Project Mu, a fork of TianoCore EDK II used in Microsoft Surface and Hyper-V products.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The project incorporates a service-based firmware delivery model.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The latest UEFI specification, version 2.11, was published in December 2024.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI supports processor architectures that are 32-bit or higher.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] However, only processors with a little-endian mode are supported.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Unofficial UEFI support is under development for POWERPC64 by implementing TianoCore EDK II on top of OPAL, the OpenPOWER abstraction layer, running in little-endian mode.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For MIPS, there also exists an unofficial project, based on the original EDK.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] However, both projects have since been abandoned as of November 2016 and September 2015 respectively.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI only allows executing UEFI applications that match the firmware's bit-width, even if the processor supports smaller or larger bit-widths.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For example, a 64-bit UEFI firmware may only execute 64-bit UEFI applications, even if the processor has a 32-bit processor mode.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Some low-end computers have been shipped with 32-bit UEFI firmware running on 64-bit CPUs.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Once a UEFI application ends the boot services and gets granted full control over the system, it becomes possible to change the processor execution mode.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] However, calling runtime services requires shortly changing back to the original processor mode, as runtime services may only be called from the same processor mode as the firmware implementation.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The Linux kernel added support for booting 64-bit kernels on 32-bit UEFI firmware implementations with x86-64 CPUs since version 3.15, requiring the UEFI boot loader to support the EFI handover protocol.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The EFI handover protocol allows UEFI boot loaders to defer the UEFI initialization to the kernel's EFI boot stub, so that only the kernel does the UEFI initialization.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In addition to the standard PC disk partition scheme that uses a master boot record (MBR), UEFI also works with the GUID Partition Table (GPT) partitioning scheme, which is free from many of the limitations of MBR.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In particular, the MBR limits on the number and size of disk partitions (up to four primary partitions per disk, and up to 2 TB (2 × 240 bytes) per disk) are relaxed.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] More specifically, GPT allows for a maximum disk and partition size of 8 ZiB (8 × 270 bytes) with 512 byte sectors.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The UEFI specification only supports FAT12/16/32 partitions that are on GPT or MBR disks as well as El Torito-formatted optical discs.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Although GPT is a part of the UEFI standard, it may also be usable by BIOS PCs to boot an operating system off of.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Support for GPT in Linux is enabled by turning on the option `CONFIG_EFI_PARTITION` (EFI GUID Partition Support) during kernel configuration.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This option allows Linux to recognize and use GPT disks after the system firmware passes control over the system to Linux.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For reverse compatibility, Linux can use GPT disks in BIOS-based systems for both data storage and booting, as both GRUB 2 and Linux are GPT-aware.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Such a setup is usually referred to as *BIOS-GPT*.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] As GPT incorporates the protective MBR, a BIOS-based computer can boot from a GPT disk using a GPT-aware boot loader stored in the protective MBR's bootstrap code area.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In the case of GRUB, such a configuration requires a BIOS boot partition for GRUB to embed its second-stage code due to absence of the post-MBR gap in GPT partitioned disks (which is taken over by the GPT's *Primary Header* and *Primary Partition Table*).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Commonly 1 MB in size, this partition's Globally Unique Identifier (GUID) in GPT scheme is 21686148-6449-6E6F-744E-656564454649 and is used by GRUB only in BIOS-GPT setups.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] From GRUB's perspective, no such partition type exists in case of MBR partitioning.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This partition is not required if the system is UEFI-based because no embedding of the second-stage code is needed in that case.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI systems can access GPT disks and boot directly from them, which allows Linux to use UEFI boot methods.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Booting Linux from GPT disks on UEFI systems involves creation of an EFI system partition (ESP), which contains UEFI applications such as bootloaders, operating system kernels, and utility software.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Such a setup is usually referred to as *UEFI-GPT*, while ESP is recommended to be at least 512 MB in size and formatted with a FAT32 filesystem for maximum compatibility.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For backward compatibility, some UEFI implementations also support booting from MBR-partitioned disks through the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) that provides legacy BIOS compatibility.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In that case, booting Linux on UEFI systems is the same as on legacy BIOS-based systems.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Windows 11, 64-bit versions of Windows Vista SP1/SP2 and 7, and both 32-bit and 64-bit versions of Windows 8, 8.1, and 10 can boot from a GPT disk that is larger than 2 TB.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] EFI defines two types of services: *boot services* and *runtime services*.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Boot services are available only while the firmware owns the platform (i.e., before the `ExitBootServices()` call), and they include text and graphical consoles on various devices, and bus, block and file services.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Runtime services are still accessible while the operating system is running; they include services such as date, time and NVRAM access.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI variables provide a way to store data, in particular non-volatile data.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Some UEFI variables are shared between platform firmware and operating systems.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Variable namespaces are identified by GUIDs, and variables are key/value pairs.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] after a crash for the operating system to retrieve after a reboot.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI executes independent programs known as UEFI applications, which are stored as files on the EFI system partition.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] These can be launched via the UEFI Shell, the firmware boot manager, or other UEFI applications, and may be developed independently of the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] A type of UEFI application is an OS boot loader such as GRUB, rEFInd, systemd-boot, and Windows Boot Manager, which loads some OS files into memory and executes them.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Also, an OS boot loader can provide a user interface to allow the selection of another UEFI application to run.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Utilities like the UEFI Shell are also UEFI applications.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] EFI defines protocols as a set of software interfaces used for communication between two binary modules.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] All EFI drivers must provide services to others via protocols.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The EFI Protocols are similar to the BIOS interrupt calls.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In addition to standard instruction set architecture-specific device drivers, EFI provides for an ISA-independent device driver stored in non-volatile memory as *EFI byte code* or *EBC*.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] System firmware has an interpreter for EBC images.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In that sense, EBC is analogous to Open Firmware, the ISA-independent firmware used in PowerPC-based Apple Macintosh and Sun Microsystems SPARC computers, among others.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Some architecture-specific (non-EFI Byte Code) EFI drivers for some device types can have interfaces for use by the OS.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This allows the OS to rely on EFI for drivers to perform basic graphics and network functions before, and if, operating-system-specific drivers are loaded.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In other cases, the EFI driver can be filesystem drivers that allow for booting from other types of disk volumes.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Examples include *efifs* for 37 file systems (based on GRUB2 code), used by Rufus for chain-loading NTFS ESPs.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The EFI 1.0 specification defined a UGA (Universal Graphic Adapter) protocol as a way to support graphics features.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI did not include UGA and replaced it with GOP (Graphics Output Protocol).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI 2.1 defined a "Human Interface Infrastructure" (HII) to manage user input, localized strings, fonts, and forms (in the HTML sense).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] These enable original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) or independent BIOS vendors (IBVs) to design graphical interfaces for pre-boot configuration.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI uses UTF-16 to encode strings by default; since at least UEFI 2.4, it allows using ASCII to encode ASCII-only strings.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Most early UEFI firmware implementations were console-based.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Today many UEFI firmware implementations are GUI-based.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] An EFI system partition, often abbreviated to ESP, is a data storage device partition that is used in computers adhering to the UEFI specification.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Accessed by the UEFI firmware when a computer is powered up, it stores UEFI applications and the files these applications need to run, including operating system boot loaders.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Supported partition table schemes include MBR and GPT, as well as El Torito volumes on optical discs.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For use on ESPs, UEFI defines a specific version of the FAT file system, which is maintained as part of the UEFI specification and independently from the original FAT specification, encompassing the FAT32, FAT16 and FAT12 file systems.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The ESP also provides space for a boot sector as part of the backward BIOS compatibility.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Computers are started up by a process which has been called booting: the computer loads its operating software by means of a very small program built into the hardware, which typically loads a program, still small, to load and start the operating system (OS).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Unlike the legacy PC BIOS, UEFI does not rely on boot sectors on the computer's data storage, defining instead a boot manager as part of the UEFI specification.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] When a computer is powered on, the boot manager checks the boot configuration and, based on its settings, then executes the specified OS boot loader or operating system kernel.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The boot configuration is defined by variables stored in the computer's persistent NVRAM storage, including variables that indicate the file system paths to OS loaders or OS kernels.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] OS boot loaders can be automatically detected by UEFI, which enables easy booting from removable devices such as USB flash drives.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This automated detection relies on standardized file paths to the OS boot loader, with the path varying depending on the computer architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The format of the file path is defined as <EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>\EFI\BOOT\BOOT<MACHINE_TYPE_SHORT_NAME>.EFI; for example, the file path to the OS loader on an x86-64 system is \efi\boot\bootx64.efi, and \efi\boot\bootaa64.efi on ARM64 architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Booting UEFI systems from GPT-partitioned disks is commonly called *UEFI-GPT booting*, although the UEFI specification requires MBR partition tables to be fully supported.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Some UEFI firmware implementations immediately switch to BIOS-based CSM booting depending on the type of the boot disk's partition table, effectively preventing UEFI booting from an EFI System Partition on MBR-partitioned disks; such a boot scheme is commonly called *UEFI-MBR*.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] It is also common for a boot manager to have a textual user interface to allow the user to select the desired OS (or setup utility) from a list of available boot options.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] On PC platforms, firmware supporting UEFI boot is often referred to as a "UEFI BIOS", though some newer x86 platforms exclude CSM support entirely.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] To ensure backward compatibility, UEFI firmware implementations on PC-class machines could support booting in legacy BIOS mode from MBR-partitioned disks through the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) that provides legacy BIOS compatibility.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In this scenario, booting is performed in the same way as on legacy BIOS-based systems, by ignoring the partition table and relying on the content of a boot sector.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The Compatibility Support Module allows legacy operating systems and some legacy option ROMs that do not support UEFI to still be used.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] It also provides required legacy System Management Mode (SMM) functionality (CompatibilitySmm) in addition to features provided by the UEFI SMM.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] An example of such a legacy SMM functionality is providing USB legacy support for keyboard and mouse, by emulating their classic PS/2 counterparts.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In November 2017, Intel announced that it planned to phase out support CSM for client platforms by 2020.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In July 2022, Kaspersky Labs published information regarding a Rootkit designed to chain boot malicious code on machines using Intel's H81 chipset and the Compatibility Support Module of affected motherboards.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In August 2023, Intel announced that it planned to phase out CSM support for server platforms by 2024.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The UEFI specification includes support for booting over network via the Preboot Execution Environment (PXE).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] PXE booting network protocols include Internet Protocol (IPv4 and IPv6), User Datagram Protocol (UDP), Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP), Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) and iSCSI.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] OS images can be remotely stored on storage area networks (SANs), with Internet Small Computer System Interface (iSCSI) and Fibre Channel over Ethernet (FCoE) as supported protocols for accessing the SANs.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Version 2.5 of the UEFI specification adds support for accessing boot images over HTTP.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The UEFI specification defines a Secure Boot that can secure the boot process by preventing the loading of UEFI drivers or OS boot loaders that are not signed with an acceptable digital signature.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] When Secure Boot is enabled, it is initially placed in "setup" mode, which allows a public key known as the "platform key" (PK) to be written to the firmware.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Once the key is written, Secure Boot enters "User" mode, where only UEFI drivers and OS boot loaders signed with the platform key can be loaded by the firmware.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Additional "key exchange keys" (KEK) can be added to a database stored in memory to allow other certificates to be used, but they must still have a connection to the private portion of the platform key.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Secure Boot can also be placed in "Custom" mode, where additional public keys can be added to the system that do not match the private key.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] As of January 2025, FreeBSD support is in its planning stage.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI provides a shell environment, which can be used to execute other UEFI applications, including UEFI boot loaders.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Source code for a UEFI shell can be downloaded from the Intel's TianoCore UDK/EDK2 project.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] A pre-built ShellBinPkg is also available.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Shell v2 works best in UEFI 2.3+ systems and is recommended over Shell v1 in those systems.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Shell v1 should work in all UEFI systems.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Methods used for launching UEFI shell depend on the manufacturer and model of the system motherboard.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Some of them already provide a direct option in firmware setup for launching, e.g. compiled x86-64 version of the shell needs to be made available as `<EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>/SHELLX64.EFI`.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Some other systems have an already embedded UEFI shell which can be launched by appropriate key press combinations.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For other systems, the solution is either creating an appropriate USB flash drive or adding manually (`bcfg`) a boot option associated with the compiled version of shell.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The following is a list of commands supported by the EFI shell.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Extensions to UEFI can be loaded from virtually any non-volatile storage device attached to the computer.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For example, an original equipment manufacturer (OEM) can distribute systems with an EFI system partition on the hard drive, which would add additional functions to the standard UEFI firmware stored on the motherboard's ROM.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI Capsule defines a firmware-to-OS firmware update interface.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Windows 8, Windows 8.1, Windows 10, and Fwupd for Linux each support the UEFI Capsule.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Like BIOS, UEFI initializes and tests system hardware components, and then loads the boot loader from a mass storage device or through a network connection.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In x86 systems, the UEFI firmware is usually stored in the NOR flash chip of the motherboard, and the boot process is more complex, for example PCI Express devices detection and initialization.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In some ARM-based Android and Windows Phone devices, the UEFI boot loader is stored in the eMMC or eUFS flash memory.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Starting from the 10th Gen Intel Core, Intel no longer provides Legacy Video BIOS for the iGPU (Intel Graphics Technology).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Legacy boot with those CPUs requires a Legacy Video BIOS, which can still be provided by a video card.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This is the first stage of the UEFI boot but may have platform specific binary code that precedes it.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] (e.g., Intel ME, AMD PSP, CPU microcode).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] It consists of minimal code written in assembly language for the specific architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] It initializes a temporary memory (often CPU cache-as-RAM (CAR), or SoC on-chip boot processor) and serves as the system's software root of trust with the option of verifying PEI before hand-off.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The second stage of UEFI boot consists of a dependency-aware dispatcher that loads and runs PEI modules (PEIMs) to handle early hardware initialization tasks such as main memory initialization (initialize memory controller and DRAM) and firmware recovery operations.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Additionally, it is responsible for discovery of the current boot mode and handling many ACPI S3 operations.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In the case of ACPI S3 resume, it is responsible for restoring many hardware registers to a pre-sleep state.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Initialization at this stage involves creating data structures in memory and establishing default values within these structures.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This stage has several components including PEI foundation, PEIMs and PPI.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Due to less resources available in this stage, this stage must be minimal and do minimal preparations for the next stage, DXE, which is richer.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] After SEC phase hand off, platform responsibility is taken by PEI Foundation.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This component is responsible for invoking PEIMs and managing their dependencies.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] These are minimal PEI drivers that are responsible for initialization of hardware components, such as permanent memory, CPU, chipset and motherboard.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Each of the PEIMs have single responsibilities and focus on single initialization.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] These drivers come from different vendors.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This is a data structure that composed of GUID pairs of pointers.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] PPIs are discovered by PEIMs through PEI services.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] After minimal initialization of the system for DXE, PEI foundation locates and passes control to DXE.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The PEI foundation dispatches DXE foundation through special PPI called IPL (Initial Program Load).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This stage consists of C modules and a dependency-aware dispatcher.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] With main memory now available, CPU, chipset, mainboard and other I/O devices are initialized in DXE and BDS.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Initialization at this stage involves assigning EFI device paths to the hardware connected to the motherboard, and transferring configuration data to the hardware.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In this stage, boot devices are initialized, UEFI drivers or Option ROMs of PCI devices are executed according to architecturally defined variables called **NVRAM**, and the operating system boot loaders (such as Windows Boot Manager) are started.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This is the stage between boot device selection and hand-off to the OS.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] At this point one may enter a UEFI shell, or execute a UEFI application such as the OS boot loader.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The UEFI hands off to the operating system (OS) after ExitBootServices() is executed.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] A UEFI compatible OS is now responsible for exiting boot services triggering the firmware to unload all no longer needed code and data, leaving only runtime services code/data, e.g.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] A typical modern OS will prefer to use its own programs (such as kernel drivers) to control hardware devices.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] When a legacy OS is used, CSM will handle this call ensuring the system is compatible with legacy BIOS expectations.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Intel's implementation of EFI is the *Intel Platform Innovation Framework*, codenamed *Tiano*.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Tiano runs on Intel's XScale, Itanium, IA-32 and x86-64 processors, and is proprietary software, although a portion of the code has been released under the BSD license or Eclipse Public License (EPL) as TianoCore EDK II.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] TianoCore can be used as a payload for coreboot.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Phoenix Technologies' implementation of UEFI is branded as SecureCore Technology (SCT).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] American Megatrends offers its own UEFI firmware implementation known as Aptio, while Insyde Software offers InsydeH2O, and Byosoft offers ByoCore.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In December 2018, Microsoft released an open source version of its TianoCore EDK2-based UEFI implementation from the Surface line, Project Mu.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] An implementation of the UEFI API was introduced into the Universal Boot Loader (Das U-Boot) in 2017.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] On the ARMv8 architecture Linux distributions use the U-Boot UEFI implementation in conjunction with GNU GRUB for booting (e.g.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] SUSE Linux), the same holds true for OpenBSD.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For booting from iSCSI iPXE can be used as a UEFI application loaded by U-Boot.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Intel's first Itanium workstations and servers, released in 2000, implemented EFI 1.02.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Hewlett-Packard's first Itanium 2 systems, released in 2002, implemented EFI 1.10.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] These systems were able to boot Windows, Linux, FreeBSD and HP-UX.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] OpenVMS added UEFI capability in June 2003.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In January 2006, Apple Inc. shipped its first Intel-based Macintosh computers.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] These systems used EFI instead of Open Firmware, which had been used on its previous PowerPC-based systems.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] On 5 April 2006, Apple first released Boot Camp, which produces a Windows drivers disk and a non-destructive partitioning tool to allow the installation of Windows XP or Vista without requiring a reinstallation of Mac OS X (now macOS).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] A firmware update was also released that added BIOS compatibility to its EFI implementation.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Subsequent Macintosh models shipped with the newer firmware.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] During 2005, more than one million Intel systems shipped with Intel's implementation of UEFI.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] New mobile, desktop and server products, using Intel's implementation of UEFI, started shipping in 2006.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For instance, boards that use the Intel 945 chipset series use Intel's UEFI firmware implementation.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Since 2005, EFI has also been implemented on non-PC architectures, such as embedded systems based on XScale cores.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The EDK (EFI Developer Kit) includes an NT32 target, which allows EFI firmware and EFI applications to run within a Windows application.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] However, no direct hardware access is allowed by EDK NT32.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This means only a subset of EFI application and drivers can be executed by the EDK NT32 target.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In 2008, more x86-64 systems adopted UEFI.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] While many of these systems still allow booting only the BIOS-based OSes via the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) (thus not appearing to the user to be UEFI-based), other systems started to allow booting UEFI-based OSes.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] For example, IBM x3450 server, MSI motherboards with ClickBIOS and HP EliteBook Notebook PCs.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In 2009, IBM shipped System x machines (x3550 M2, x3650 M2, iDataPlex dx360 M2) and BladeCenter HS22 with UEFI capability.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Dell shipped PowerEdge T610, R610, R710, M610 and M710 servers with UEFI capability.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] More commercially available systems are mentioned in a UEFI whitepaper.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In 2011, major vendors (such as ASRock, Asus, Gigabyte, and MSI) launched several consumer-oriented motherboards using the Intel 6-series LGA 1155 chipset and AMD 9 Series AM3+ chipsets with UEFI.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] With the release of Windows 8 in October 2012, Microsoft's certification requirements now require that computers include firmware that implements the UEFI specification.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Furthermore, if the computer supports the "Connected Standby" feature of Windows 8 (which allows devices to have power management comparable to smartphones, with an almost instantaneous return from standby mode), then the firmware is not permitted to contain a Compatibility Support Module (CSM).
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] As such, systems that support Connected Standby are incapable of booting Legacy BIOS operating systems.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In October 2017, Intel announced that it would remove legacy PC BIOS support from all its products by 2020, in favor of UEFI Class 3.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] By 2019, all computers based on Intel platforms no longer have legacy PC BIOS support.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] A operating system that can be booted from (U)EFI is called a (U)EFI-aware operating system, defined by (U)EFI specification.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Here the term *booted from a (U)EFI* means directly booting the system using a (U)EFI operating system loader stored on any storage device.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The default location for the operating system loader is `<EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>/BOOT/BOOT<MACHINE_TYPE_SHORT_NAME>.EFI`, where short name of the machine type can be `IA32`, `X64`, `IA64`, `ARM` or `AA64`.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Some operating systems vendors may have their own boot loaders.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] They may also change the default boot location.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] UEFI implementation flaws have been exploited to gain persistence, the ability to maintain malicious access to a compromised system even after system reboot, operating system reinstallation, and even partial physical part replacement, such as of corrupted PCI persistent flash storage.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] There were vulnerabilities in 2023 even with Secure Boot enabled.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In 2023 Microsoft published a warning about BlackLotus UEFI malware.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Numerous digital rights activists have protested UEFI.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Minnich, a co-author of coreboot, and Cory Doctorow, a digital rights activist, have criticized UEFI as an attempt to remove the ability of the user to truly control the computer.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Critics, such as coreboot co-author Ronald G.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Minnich, argue that UEFI maintains the historic arrangement of requiring two separate drivers—one for the firmware and one for the operating system—for most hardware.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Open-source project TianoCore also provides UEFIs.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] TianoCore lacks the specialized firmware drivers and modules that initialize chipset functions, but TianoCore is one of many payload options of coreboot.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] The development of coreboot requires cooperation from chipset manufacturers to provide the specifications needed to develop initialization drivers.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In 2011, Microsoft announced that computers certified to run its Windows 8 operating system had to ship with Microsoft's public key enrolled and Secure Boot enabled, which implies that using UEFI is a requirement for these devices.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Following the announcement, critics and free-software/open-source advocates, including the Free Software Foundation, expressed concern that Microsoft might use the Secure Boot functionality of UEFI to restrict the installation of alternative operating systems such as Linux.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Microsoft denied that the Secure Boot requirement was intended to serve as a form of lock-in and clarified its requirements by stating that x86-based systems certified for Windows 8 must allow Secure Boot to enter custom mode or be disabled, but not on systems using the ARM architecture.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Windows 10 allows OEMs to decide whether or not Secure Boot can be managed by users of their x86 systems.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Other developers raised concerns about the legal and practical issues of implementing support for Secure Boot on Linux systems in general.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Other developers suggested that signed builds of Linux with another key could be provided, but noted that it would be difficult to persuade OEMs to ship their computers with the required key alongside the Microsoft key.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Several major Linux distributions have developed different implementations for Secure Boot.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Garrett himself developed a minimal bootloader known as a shim, which is a precompiled, signed bootloader that allows the user to individually trust keys provided by Linux distributions.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] That also allows users to build their own kernels and use custom kernel modules as well, without the need to reconfigure the system.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Fedora also uses shim, but requires that both the kernel and its modules be signed as well. shim has Machine Owner Key (MOK) that can be used to sign locally compiled kernels and other software not signed by distribution maintainer, without changing the Secure Boot mode to setup mode.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In Windows, if Secure Boot is enabled, all kernel drivers must be digitally signed; non-WHQL drivers may be refused to load.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In February 2013, another Red Hat developer attempted to submit a patch to the Linux kernel that would allow it to parse Microsoft's authenticode signing using a master X.509 key embedded in PE files signed by Microsoft.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] However, the proposal was criticized by Linux creator Linus Torvalds, who argued that Red Hat was accommodating Microsoft's control over the Secure Boot infrastructure.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] On 26 March 2013, the Spanish free-software development group Hispalinux filed a formal complaint with the European Commission, contending that Microsoft's Secure Boot requirements on OEM systems were "obstructive" and anti-competitive.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] At the Black Hat conference in August 2013, a group of security researchers presented a series of exploits in specific vendor implementations of UEFI that could be used to exploit Secure Boot.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In August 2016 it was reported that two security researchers had found the "golden key" security key Microsoft uses in signing operating systems.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Technically, no key was exposed, but an exploitable binary signed by the key was.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This allows software to execute as though it were signed by Microsoft, presenting potential risks for rootkit and bootkit attacks.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] This also complicates remediation efforts, since a patch can potentially be downgraded by replacing it with the signed exploitable binary.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Microsoft stated that the vulnerability only affects ARM architecture and Windows RT devices and released two updates; however, reports noted that these updates do not completely prevent exploitation because fully resolving the vulnerability would require key replacements in end-user firmware.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] On 1 March 2023, researchers from ESET reported discovering "BlackLotus", described as the first active UEFI bootkit capable of bypassing UEFI Secure Boot by exploiting the limitations of the previous security updates.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In August 2024, the Windows 11 and Windows 10 security updates applied the Secure Boot Advanced Targeting (SBAT) settings to device's UEFI NVRAM, which caused some Linux distributions to fail to load.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] SBAT is a protocol that supported in new versions of Windows Boot Manager and shim, which refuse buggy or vulnerable intermediate bootloaders (usually older versions of Windows Boot Manager and GRUB) to load in the boot process.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In June 2025, LWN.net reported that the Microsoft UEFI CA 2011 certificate will be expired on June 27, 2026, which may refuse some Linux to load if Secure Boot is enabled.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] However, in TianoCore EDK II as well as many commercial UEFI implementations (such as AMI Aptio), time/date check for Secure Boot certificate is usually disabled by default.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Many Linux distributions support UEFI Secure Boot as of January 2025, such as RHEL (RHEL 7 and later), CentOS (CentOS 7 and later), Ubuntu, Fedora, Debian (Debian 10 and later), OpenSUSE, and SUSE Linux Enterprise.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] A number of technical issues have been reported regarding specific implementations of UEFI firmware in commercial devices.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] Similar operational difficulties were reported regarding several Toshiba laptop models where specific firmware certificates required for Secure Boot operation were missing.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] In January 2013, a firmware issue was publicized regarding the UEFI implementation on certain Samsung laptops, which rendered the devices completely inoperable after a Linux distribution was installed in UEFI mode.
[src:bootloader-security/secure-boot] His analysis concluded that the associated kernel module caused kernel message dumps to be written to the firmware storage space, executing the failure state.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] A **trusted execution environment** (**TEE**) is a secure area of a main processor.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] It helps the code and data loaded inside it be protected with respect to confidentiality and integrity.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Data confidentiality prevents unauthorized entities from outside the TEE from reading data, while code integrity prevents code in the TEE from being replaced or modified by unauthorized entities, which may also be the computer owner itself as in certain DRM schemes described in Intel SGX.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] This is done by implementing unique, immutable, and confidential architectural security, which offers hardware-based memory encryption that isolates specific application code and data in memory.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] This allows user-level code to allocate private regions of memory, called enclaves, which are designed to be protected from processes running at higher privilege levels.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE as an isolated execution environment provides security features such as isolated execution, integrity of applications executing with the TEE, and confidentiality of their assets.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] In general terms, the TEE offers an execution space that provides a higher level of security for trusted applications running on the device than a rich operating system (OS) and more functionality than a 'secure element' (SE).
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The first security level, Profile 1, was targeted against only software attacks, while Profile 2, was targeted against both software and hardware attacks.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Commercial TEE solutions based on ARM TrustZone technology, conforming to the TR1 standard, were later launched, such as Trusted Foundations developed by Trusted Logic.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Work on the OMTP standards ended in mid-2010 when the group transitioned into the Wholesale Applications Community (WAC).
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The OMTP standards, including those defining a TEE, are hosted by GSMA.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE typically consists of a hardware isolation mechanism plus a secure operating system running on top of that isolation mechanism, although the term has been used more generally to mean a protected solution.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Whilst a GlobalPlatform TEE requires hardware isolation, others, such as EMVCo, use the term TEE to refer to both hardware and software-based solutions.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] FIDO uses the concept of TEE in the restricted operating environment for TEEs based on hardware isolation.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Only trusted applications running in a TEE have access to the full power of a device's main processor, peripherals, and memory, while hardware isolation protects these from user-installed apps running in a main operating system.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Software and cryptography inside the TEE protects the trusted applications contained within from each other.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Service providers, mobile network operators (MNO), operating system developers, application developers, device manufacturers, platform providers, and silicon vendors are the main stakeholders contributing to the standardization efforts around the TEE.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] To prevent the simulation of hardware with user-controlled software, a so-called "hardware root of trust" is used.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] This is a set of private keys that are embedded directly into the chip during manufacturing; one-time programmable memory such as eFuses is usually used on mobile devices.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The hardware is designed in a way that prevents all software not signed by the trusted party's key from accessing the privileged features.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The public key of the vendor is provided at runtime and hashed; this hash is then compared to the one embedded in the chip.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] If the hash matches, the public key is used to verify a digital signature of trusted vendor-controlled firmware (such as a chain of bootloaders on Android devices or 'architectural enclaves' in SGX).
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The trusted firmware is then used to implement remote attestation.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] When an application is attested, its untrusted components loads its trusted component into memory; the trusted application is protected from modification by untrusted components with hardware.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] A nonce is requested by the untrusted party from the verifier's server and is used as part of a cryptographic authentication protocol, proving integrity of the trusted application.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The proof is passed to the verifier, which verifies it.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] A valid proof cannot be computed in simulated hardware (i.e.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] QEMU) because in order to construct it, access to the keys baked into hardware is required; only trusted firmware has access to these keys and/or the keys derived from them or obtained using them.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Because only the platform owner is meant to have access to the data recorded in the foundry, the verifying party must interact with the service set up by the vendor.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] If the scheme is implemented improperly, the chip vendor can track which applications are used on which chip and selectively deny service by returning a message indicating that authentication has not passed.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] To simulate hardware in a way that enables it to pass remote authentication, an attacker would have to extract keys from the hardware, which is costly because of the equipment and technical skill required to execute it.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] For example, using focused ion beams, scanning electron microscopes, microprobing, and chip decapsulation is difficult, or even impossible, if the hardware is designed in such a way that reverse-engineering destroys the keys.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] In most cases, the keys are unique for each piece of hardware, so that a key extracted from one chip cannot be used by others (for example physically unclonable functions).
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Note: Much TEE literature covers this topic under the definition "premium content protection," which is the preferred nomenclature of many copyright holders.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Premium content protection is a specific use case of digital rights management (DRM) and is controversial among some communities, such as the Free Software Foundation.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] It is widely used by copyright holders to restrict the ways in which end users can consume content such as 4K high-definition films.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is a suitable environment for protecting digitally encoded information (for example, HD films or audio) on connected devices such as smartphones, tablets, and HD televisions.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] This suitability comes from the ability of the TEE to deprive the owner of the device of access stored secrets, and the fact that there is often a protected hardware path between the TEE and the display and/or subsystems on devices.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is used to protect the content once it is on the device.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] While the content is protected during transmission or streaming by the use of encryption, the TEE protects the content once it has been decrypted on the device by ensuring that decrypted content is not exposed to the environment not approved by the app developer or platform vendor.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Mobile commerce applications such as: mobile wallets, peer-to-peer payments, contactless payments or using a mobile device as a point of sale (POS) terminal often have well-defined security requirements.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] In some scenarios, interaction with the end user is required, and this may require the user to expose sensitive information such as a PIN, password, or biometric identifier to the mobile OS as a means of authenticating the user.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE optionally offers a trusted user interface which can be used to construct user authentication on a mobile device.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of cryptocurrency, TEEs are increasingly used to implement crypto-wallets, as they offer the ability to store tokens more securely than regular operating systems, and can provide the necessary computation and authentication applications.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is well-suited for supporting biometric identification methods (facial recognition, fingerprint sensor, and voice authorization), which may be easier to use and harder to steal than PINs and passwords.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE is a good area within a mobile device to house the matching engine and the associated processing required to authenticate the user.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The environment is designed to protect the data and establish a buffer against the non-secure apps located in mobile OSes.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] This additional security may help to satisfy the security needs of service providers in addition to keeping the costs low for handset developers.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE can be used by governments, enterprises, and cloud service providers to enable the secure handling of confidential information on mobile devices and on server infrastructure.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE offers a level of protection against software attacks generated in the mobile OS and assists in the control of access rights.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] It achieves this by housing sensitive, ‘trusted’ applications that need to be isolated and protected from the mobile OS and any malicious malware that may be present.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Through utilizing the functionality and security levels offered by the TEE, governments, and enterprises can be assured that employees using their own devices are doing so in a secure and trusted manner.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] Likewise, server-based TEEs help defend against internal and external attacks against backend infrastructure.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of software assets and reuses, modular programming is the most productive process to design software architecture, by decoupling the functionalities into small independent modules.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] As each module contains everything necessary to execute its desired functionality, the TEE allows the organization of the complete system featuring a high level of reliability and security, while preventing each module from vulnerabilities of the others.
[src:bootloader-security/trusted-execution-environment] In order for the modules to communicate and share data, TEE provides means to securely have payloads sent/received between the modules, using mechanisms such as object serialization, in conjunction with proxies.
